4. In the opinion of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, Soviet tactics since World
                        War II reflect certain basic tenets of Soviet doctrine and strategy;
                        viz.:

list.item:
i. In negotiations, Soviet objectives are to be sought by:
(1) Inflexible adherence to demands, even fantastic ones, coupled with resistance from the outset to counter-proposals;
(2) Yielding to no substantive concessions; a concession by the “enemy” is to be treated merely as an indication that persistence in negotiation may extract further and perhaps greater advantages;
(3) Disregarding any accepted code of ethics or any conception of honor in the conduct of negotiations or in the carrying out of any agreements which might flow from them.

a. The foregoing views be made available to the National Security
                            Council for consideration in the application of basic national
                            policy;

